ingdom"},"nl":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzSimon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English, Irish: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + either of the personal names  <i>Simon</i> or  <i>Sigmund</i> (  see  Simon  ), ‘son of  <i>Simon</i> or  <i>Sigmund</i>’. In Ireland this name has been gaelicized as  <b>Mac Síomóin</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitzsimmons","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of <b>Fitzsimon</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + either of the personal names <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i> (see   Simon  ), ‘son of <i>Simon</i> or <i>Sigmund</i>’. The name is also found in the Gaelicized form <b>Mac Síomóin</b>."]},{"name":"Simon","meanings":["English (Lancashire), French, Walloon, Breton, German, Dutch, Hungarian, northern Italian, and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Spanish (<b>Simón</b>); Czech and Slovak (mainly <b>Šimon</b>); Slovenian, Croatian, and Rusyn (from Slovakia) (also <b>Šimon</b>): from the Biblical personal name, Hebrew <i>Shim‘on</i>, which is probably derived from the Hebrew verb <i>sham‘a</i> ‘to hearken’. In the Vulgate and in many vernacular versions of the Old Testament, this is usually rendered   Simeon  . In the Greek New Testament, however, the name occurs as <i>Simōn</i>, as a result of assimilation to the pre-existing Greek byname <i>Sīmōn</i> (from <i>sīmos</i> ‘snub-nosed’). Both <i>Simon</i> and <i>Simeon</i> were in use as personal names in western Europe from the Middle Ages onward. In Christendom the former was always more popular, at least in part because of its associations with the apostle Simon Peter, the brother of Andrew. In Britain there was also confusion from an early date with Anglo-Scandinavian forms of <i>Sigmund(r)</i> or <i>Sigmund</i> (see   Siegmund  ), a name whose popularity was reinforced at the Conquest by the Norman form <i>Simund</i>. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Simone  , Polish <b>Szymon</b>, Albanian   Simoni  , and Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic <b>Shimun</b>,   Shamon  , or   Shamoun  , and also their derivatives (see examples at   Simons  ). See also   Shimon  .","History: André Simon <i>dit</i> Boucher from France married Marie Martin in Acadia <i>c.</i> 1688. François Simon from Saint-Pair-sur-Mer in Manche, France, married Marie-Dorothée Gagnon in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1744."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Rafe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spelling representation of the traditional pronunciation of the name   Ralph  , a pronunciation now largely restricted to the upper classes in England."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Rafe FitzSimon was born in 1079, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Simon FitzSimon. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1148, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir Rafe FitzSimon est né en 1079, à Lancaster, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Simon FitzSimon. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1148, à Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 69 ans."},"de":{"1079–1148":"1079–1148","1117–1140":"1117–1140","1043–1118":"1043–1118","1118":"1118","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1079":"1079","1043":"1043","1140":"1140","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, Uni